Here's the audit. I found **7 problems** across 8 tests — most would pass even when the code is wrong.

---

**🔴 Critical — Tests that verify nothing:**

**`GetUser_NonExistentId_ReturnsNull`** — Zero assertions. The comment `// should be null` replaces an actual check. This always passes.
```csharp
// Fix: Assert.IsNull(user);
```

**`AddUser_DuplicateId_ThrowsException`** — Swallowed exception via try/catch. If no exception is thrown, the test **still passes** silently (falls through). This is likely your prod incident.
```csharp
// Fix: Assert.ThrowsException<InvalidOperationException>(() => repo.Add(new User(1, "Bob")));
```

**`DeleteUser_RemovesFromRepository`** — `Assert.AreEqual(repo.Count, repo.Count)` compares the value **to itself**. Always passes regardless of whether Delete works.
```csharp
// Fix: Assert.AreEqual(0, repo.Count);
```

---

**🟡 Moderate — Weak/misleading assertions:**

**`GetUser_ExistingId_ReturnsUser`** — Only checks `IsNotNull`. Never verifies `Id` or `Name`. Would pass if the wrong user were returned.
```csharp
// Fix: Assert.AreEqual("Alice", user.Name); Assert.AreEqual(1, user.Id);
```

**`UpdateUser_ChangesName`** — `Assert.IsTrue(user.Name != "Alice")` is a negative check. Would pass if `Name` were `""`, `null`, or any garbage. Assert the expected value directly.
```csharp
// Fix: Assert.AreEqual("Alicia", user.Name);
```

**`AddUser_NullUser_ThrowsArgumentNullException`** — Name says `ArgumentNullException` but asserts `ThrowsException<Exception>` (base type). Would catch any unrelated exception and pass.
```csharp
// Fix: Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(() => repo.Add(null!));
```

---

**🟢 Minor:**

**`SearchUsers_ByPartialName_FindsMatches`** — Uses `Assert.IsTrue(results.Count == 2)` instead of `Assert.AreEqual(2, results.Count)`. On failure you'd get *"Assert.IsTrue failed"* with no actual/expected values. Also doesn't verify *which* users matched.

**Unused field** — `static HttpClient _client` is never used. Dead code or a forgotten external dependency leaking into unit tests.

---

**`GetAllUsers_ReturnsCorrectCount`** is the only well-written test — good count check plus content verification.

The three critical tests (`NonExistentId`, `DuplicateId`, `Delete`) are the most dangerous — they pass unconditionally and likely masked the production bug.
